               <p>JOHN GARRETT. I live in <placeName id="t18280911-203-crimeloc1042">Carburton-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-203-crimeloc1042" type="placeName" value="Carburton-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280911-203-crimeloc1042" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-203-off1040 t18280911-203-crimeloc1042"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18280911-203-viclabel1043" type="occupation">carver and gilder</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-203-victim1178 t18280911-203-viclabel1043"></join>. The prisoner had been my <rs id="t18280911-203-deflabel1044" type="occupation">nurse</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280911-203-defend1177 t18280911-203-deflabel1044"></join>; my wife was ill - she had been with me about four weeks, and had attended Mrs. Garrett in her confinement before; I had some suspicion of her - and on the evening of the 15th of August, about 8 o'clock, she went out; I sent a man to bring her back - she came back, and had a bundle; I said I suspected she had been robbing me - she said No; Mrs. Garrett had given her part of the things, and the other part she had lent her; I found in the bundle two wine-bottles, a gown, a prayer-book, a silk handkerchief, a petticoat, a muslin collar, and other things - we then searched her pockets, and found a bag of flour, some potatoes, some salts and wafers; she said she had taken them, or words to that effect, and begged to be forgiven.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-203-person1179">
                  SAMUEL 
                  EVANS
               <interp inst="t18280911-203-person1179" type="surname" value="EVANS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-203-person1179" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280911-203-person1179" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I took the prisoner, and searched her; I found the articles the prosecutor has stated, and a great many more - the prisoner said Mrs. Garret had given her some, and lent her others; I found a furniture-brush under her arm, and some other things - the prosecutor claimed them all; she said she hoped she should be forgiven.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written defence, stating that her misthress had given her the salts to conceal them from her master.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280911-203-person1180">
                  JOHN 
                  GARRETT
               <interp inst="t18280911-203-person1180" type="surname" value="GARRETT"></interp>
